
A standard for operating systems.

POSIX = ISO/IEC 9945 (aka IEEE 1003).

To some extent, the *System V Interface Description* is a superset of POSIX.

{ Syscalls #syscalls

  → Linux/kernel/sys-calls[Syscalls] are not part of POSIX. POSIX defines a programming interface - if
  the functionality is implemented with syscalls or not is an implementation detail.

  → http://stackoverflow.com/questions/30155858[Stackoverflow: Are Unix Linux system calls part of posix library functions].

}

sa:

  → development/environment-variable#posixly_correct,
  → development/languages/Perl/modules/POSIX/index

  Originally, → Windows came with a POSIX subsystem:
  → Windows/registry/tree/HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE/System/CurrentControlSet/Control/Session-Manager/SubSystems#reg-subsystem-posix[`HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\Session Manager\SubSystems`]

  The POSIX standard also covers the line editor → development/editors/ed[ed] and its visual «variant» vi.

  → Linux/LSB[Linux Standard Base]
